Comments: Sandy plot in a swale in widely spaced dunefield that runs north west to south east. 1.2km to the dune on north eastern edge. Dune just to the south west of the site. 1 degree slope to the north east to centre of the swale. Burnt 2-5 years- some dead material in ground layer. Grazing effect is low- some large camels foot pads through the site. Introduced plat species effect is nil.  Homogeneity- faint access track to the south west of the site. Community continues 1.2m to the north to dune and 15m to the south.

Comments: The Landform element is a hill slope with a pattern of hills. South west corner is on the ridge crest with the rest of the site slope down in northeast direction at 6-7 degrees, levelling off at the northeast corner. There are outcrops present and cobbles and some gravels and boulder. Lithology metamorphose sandstone. Site was burnt in 2013, most of the Eucalypts are still alive but a majority of the C. endlicheri are dead. Regeneration of the A. decora and A. harpophylla has probably happened since the fire. Heavily impacted by goats and some roos, most of the grasses have been heavily grazed. Introduced plant species impact is low with Heliotropium sp. and Urtica sp. present. Vegetation community is confined to the plot. Site gets more dense in southwest corner with Acacia harpophylla and some E. blakelyi on ridge line.

Comments: The area within the polygon (called Ewan Road') is famous among entomologists specialising in the beetle family Buprestidae as being a unique type of upland open Eucalyptus woodland being the dependent habitat for a diversity of Buprestidae species. The Buprestid species Castiarina brooksi is only known from this area (note: the locations for this species plotted in ALA are wrongly plotted as the species is plotted as occurring within rainforest, but in fact it only occurs in the area marked here). However in recent decades the landowner (or leasee?) has been burning this important habitat every season in order to promote grass growth for cattle. This is causing serious habitat change for the worse and is impacting the important Buprestid fauna of this area. The area and its surrounds is in need of immediate protection.

Comments:
Swamp. Straddles channel and in floodplain. Combination of channel and flood out.  River channel winds through plot on southern edge. Introduced plant effect high- Cenchrus ciliaris dominant in ground layer.  Community  opens up more outside the site to the south and north east. Grazing effect high- cattle, Kangaroos and pigs. Fire impact- long unburnt- no scarring on trees. Rainfall one month previous.
Eucalyptus coolabah low woodland with Acacia cambagei and a diverse ground stratum dominated by Cenchrus ciliaris.

Description: Assessment of the condition of sites
Attribution: Commonwealth Department of the Environment and Energy. (2018) Site Condition Assessment dataset download. Retrieved from https://biocollect.ala.org.au/bioActivity/projectRecords/405fdfe2-c22c-46c6-806d-cc7f644a0824. 12/11/2018, 09:47.
Comments:
Bassendean dune above surrounding alluvial plains. Very long unburnt- 50+ years. One or two very old burnt trees. Introduced plant species effect is low- Hypochaeris glabra present but cover low. Some other species including Zantedeschia aethiopica, Briza maxima and Romulea rosea var. australis but cover minimal. Grazing- some impact from kangaroos but not formally grazed. Homogeneity- difficult to tell exactly beyond plot due to thickness of vegetation but plot is homogenous. Track running north south to the west of the site. North west corner is about 20m in from cleared fire break along track edge. 
Allocasuarina fraseriana/ Kunzea glabrescens/ Banksia attenuata low open forest with Banksia menziesii and Eucalyptus marginata subsp. marginata.  Mid stratum is a mid open shubland dominated by Kunzea glabrescens and juvenile Banksia species. Ground stratum is alow open sedgelands dominated by Desmocladus flexuosus with Patersonia occidentalis var. occidentalis and Hypochaeris glabra.

Description: Assessment of the condition of sites
Attribution: Commonwealth Department of the Environment and Energy. (2018) Site Condition Assessment dataset download. Retrieved from https://biocollect.ala.org.au/bioActivity/projectRecords/405fdfe2-c22c-46c6-806d-cc7f644a0824. 12/11/2018, 09:47.
Comments:
A complex Hill slope  of low rises.Drainage lines run through the centre of the plot from north west to south east with the plot sloping up from this on the other side. Plot Goes over the capping at the south west corner in the opposite direction. Main slope of 4 degree to the south east. Substrate is Iron Rich sandstone/laterite. Some shallow outcrop at the south west corner.  Minimal grazing. Tree has been cut in site- firewood? but disturbance minimal otherwise. Sandier through the creek channel as well. Very long unburnt. Introduced species effect is low- some Cape weed and other species but cover is low.  Homogeneity- North west corner is 5m in from access track. Community is confined to the plot- south west corner is a little more open with more rock.

Eucalyptus accedens low open forest with Eucalyptus wandoo subsp. wandoo. Very sparse mid story- some juvenile Eucalyptus accedens and Eucalyptus wandoo subsp. wandoo. Ground stratum is diverse but sparse, dominated in very low cover by Aira cupaniana

Comments: Bed of 12 Mile Creek. Minimal surface strew- some alluvial wash in the creek. Most of the Chenopodium auricomum have been grazed by Kangaroos. 20m from south west corner is old bore and tank so would have been more heavily grazed in the past. Plot is largely flat with deeper channel of the creek flowing eastward. Community is confined to plot- south west corner rise up out of main swampy area. A shallow channel runs north close to the south west corner- deeper main bed of creek is north of that. North east corner just comes up on to sandier ridge in middle of channel which is sparser.
